prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
Sensitivity and Requested Wavelength Band:
The sensitivity requirement of 0.2 mJy/beam in the continuum is designed to provide a spatially integrated dust continuum detection threshold (3-sigma) that is a factor of ~5 deeper than all previous mm disk surveys, allowing us to distinguish between different scalings between disk and stellar host masses at the low end of the host mass distribution. This same threshold should also permit a firm (5-sigma) detection of the 13CO (and in many cases C18O) line emission, with an RMS per 61 kHz channel of ~40 mJy/beam (the 12CO line peak SNR is expected to be ~20-40 at most). Our simulations (see Figure 2 of Scientific Justification) indicate that these sensitivities are sufficient (i.e., the S/N is high enough across a range of spatial frequencies) to robustly measure the line and continuum sizes for these targets. Band 6 was selected for its unique simultaneous access to the 12CO, 13CO, and (especially) C18O emission lines, which are key diagnostics of disk sizes and gas masses, coupled with the suitable available angular resolution.
Imaging Requirements:
The maximum available baseline lengths (1.5 km, or ~0.2" nominal angular resolution) are necessary to measure the sizes/morphologies of the continuum and line emission in these targets, which are expected to have diameters down to ~0.2" (~30 AU; for the latest type hosts/faintest disks). Some targets will have ring morphologies with inner radii on the scales of ~0.2-0.5", again forcing us to take advantage of the longest baselines in Cycle 2. However, some (and perhaps many) disks harbor very extended gas reservoirs, out to scales of ~5" (800 AU) in diameter. Since the Cycle 2 extended configurations are missing short spacings (<40 m), a non-neligible fraction of the total emission (especially in spectral lines) could be filtered out (thereby biasing our results) without devoting some of the requested time to a more compact configuration. We therefore request a maximum angular scale of 5" to insure that we probe the disk emission over the full range of spatial frequencies. Our simulations and sensitivity/overhead estimates properly account for this second configuration of the 12m array, as detailed in Section 7.6 of the ALMA Cycle 2 Technical Handbook. Note that the slightly reduced image fidelity for "snapshot" observations does not impact the ability to achieve our goals, since all our measurements are performed directly on the visibilities.
Correlator Setup:
We request data in the dual-polarization mode with 4 basebands. Two of these (centered at 218 and 233 GHz) are configured in TDM mode to maximize the continuum bandwidth (and thereby sensitivity). The upper sideband contains one FDM baseband with 61 kHz channels to probe the 12CO(2-1) line at 230.538 GHz (~0.16 km/s velocity resolution; the window is slightly shifted off center of the line, to avoid the noisy edge of the sideband). The remaining baseband is divided into two narrow spectral windows, each with 61 kHz channels (and half the total bandwidth of the 12CO baseband) centered on the 13CO(2-1) and C18O(2-1) lines at 220.399 and 219.560 GHz, respectively. We expect emission line widths of ~5 km/s (4 MHz), so the specified setup should easily resolve the lines: modest binning in lower S/N targets would still ensure robust measurements to meet our scientific objectives.
Calibration: No special calibrations are required.
Bandpass accuracy: Standard calibration is sufficient.
Scheduling/time constratints: None
Data rate: Within normal limits.
Special constraints on standard observing modes: None.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose a resolved (~0.2") snapshot census of the 1.3mm continuum and 12CO/13CO/C18O J=2-1 line emission from the complete sample of protoplanetary disks in the ~2-3 Myr-old Cha-I association. This unbiased and uniform (in both sensitivity and angular resolution) survey will facilitate some fundamental demographic analyses of the properties and evolution of protoplanetary disks, including: (1) measurements of the line and continuum intensity and size/morphology distributions (and correlations), and how they compare with other disk populations and theoretical predictions for the growth and migration of disk solids; (2) comparisons between disk masses/sizes and the properties of their stellar hosts (especially mass and multiplicity); and (3) searches for trends between disk masses/sizes and indirect evolutionary indicators, particularly the frequency and size distribution of large, central dust cavities among a sub-population of "transition" disks. Moreover, this survey will provide a valuable set of foundational data resources for the more pragmatic, strategic planning of a wide variety of disk studies in future ALMA cycles.
